WEBVTT

00:07.424 --> 00:10.593
I didn't choose Henry
and Henry didn't choose me.

00:10.677 --> 00:14.681
We just happened to each other
in the wrong order.

00:14.764 --> 00:18.601
-♪ (WHIMSICAL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
-(DOORBELL BUZZES)

00:18.685 --> 00:20.812
GOMEZ: (OVER INTERCOM)
All the way up.

00:20.895 --> 00:23.314
-Hey, it's Henry.
-GOMEZ: All the way up.

00:23.398 --> 00:25.692
(DOOR BUZZES, CLICKS OPEN)

00:25.775 --> 00:27.235
People talk about agency.

00:27.318 --> 00:30.363
All the time,
everybody's gotta have agency.

00:30.447 --> 00:31.906
Well, let me tell you something.

00:31.990 --> 00:33.658
When it comes to
falling in love,

00:34.284 --> 00:36.411
nobody has any agency.

00:36.494 --> 00:37.954
That's why they call it falling.

00:38.663 --> 00:40.039
(UTENSILS CLATTERING)

00:41.416 --> 00:43.835
Was there a photograph
with the recipe?

00:43.918 --> 00:45.086
Uh...

00:47.547 --> 00:49.466
This is supposed to be that?

00:51.301 --> 00:52.469
Are you in love?

00:53.803 --> 00:56.222
I hope so. (CHUCKLES)

00:56.306 --> 00:59.976
But ask yourself this.
When it happened,

01:00.059 --> 01:04.314
did you choose who? When? How?

01:04.397 --> 01:07.942
Is this person that now owns
a huge part of your life

01:08.026 --> 01:10.361
anything like you thought
they'd be?

01:10.445 --> 01:12.155
Did they arrive
when they were supposed to?

01:12.238 --> 01:14.532
Is any of it
anything like you planned?

01:14.616 --> 01:15.658
(SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE)

01:15.742 --> 01:18.203
Right up to the top,
just keep coming up!

01:19.496 --> 01:22.957
Yeah, well, I figured going up
was a good choice. (PANTING)

01:23.041 --> 01:25.919
You don't take decisions,
decisions take you.

01:26.002 --> 01:29.672
-Hold tight and call it a plan.
-♪ (WHIMSICAL MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

01:29.756 --> 01:31.549
I mean, it's not
that I can't cook.

01:31.633 --> 01:34.469
-It's that I choose not to.
-But you're cooking today.

01:34.552 --> 01:36.721
Yeah, well, I mean,
I'm only half cooking.

01:36.805 --> 01:37.889
Look at the chicken.

01:37.972 --> 01:39.682
So, that means
you definitely like him.

01:39.766 --> 01:42.602
(CHUCKLES) Either that
or I hate his guts.

01:42.685 --> 01:44.229
Oh, speaking of guts...

01:45.772 --> 01:47.315
The only difference
with Henry and me

01:47.398 --> 01:48.775
is that it's all mixed up.

01:48.858 --> 01:52.570
And that means, now and then,
we know what's coming.

01:52.654 --> 01:55.990
-(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)
-(HENRY DETAMBLE, 28, PANTS)

01:56.074 --> 01:58.117
Bits and pieces, not everything.

01:58.910 --> 02:00.203
A few bends in the river.

02:02.413 --> 02:04.165
Library boy!

02:04.249 --> 02:06.000
(SCOFFS) Does she call me that?

02:06.084 --> 02:07.919
-She calls you Henry.
-(SIGHS)

02:09.921 --> 02:12.423
Well, what's she call you?

02:12.507 --> 02:15.051
-Gomez.
-Hmm.

02:15.844 --> 02:16.970
Pleased to meet you.

02:20.473 --> 02:21.432
Come right in.

02:21.516 --> 02:22.809
OLDEST HENRY:
Now and then, of course,

02:22.892 --> 02:24.602
you meet someone
who hates you already...

02:24.686 --> 02:26.563
Thanks.

02:26.646 --> 02:29.440
OLDEST HENRY: ...and you have
no idea why. Yet.

02:29.524 --> 02:31.276
Wow. Nice.

02:31.359 --> 02:34.237
Oh, so you haven't been
to her apartment. (CHUCKLES)

02:34.320 --> 02:35.905
Why would you be so happy
about that?

02:35.989 --> 02:37.031
Who says I'm happy?

02:37.115 --> 02:39.117
The giant smile
on your enormous face

02:39.200 --> 02:40.577
almost took my eye out.

02:40.660 --> 02:43.538
-You make a lot of jokes.
-(GRUNTS) It's a rollercoaster.

02:43.621 --> 02:46.916
Oh, my kittens!
I have brought you a new toy.

02:47.000 --> 02:50.461
It answers to the name of Henry,
but you can call it Library Boy.

02:50.545 --> 02:53.381
-And it makes many jokes.
-Please, just call me Henry.

02:53.464 --> 02:55.592
I'm only Library Boy
when I'm fighting crime.

02:55.675 --> 02:56.801
Oh, what are your superpowers?

02:56.885 --> 02:59.262
Ah, the Dewey Decimal system
and speed shelving.

02:59.345 --> 03:00.638
Doesn't always have
the desired effect

03:00.722 --> 03:02.348
in a bank robbery,
but I live in hope.

03:02.432 --> 03:04.726
See? Funny, funny.
Made four jokes already.

03:04.809 --> 03:06.102
Who's counting? Five.

03:06.185 --> 03:07.437
-Oh, hey!
-Hey.

03:09.188 --> 03:13.276
-I'm Charisse, Clare's roommate.
-Yeah! She's with me.

03:13.359 --> 03:16.279
That's why I've been
to this apartment so many times.

03:16.362 --> 03:18.448
Yeah, I need him
for lifting heavy objects.

03:18.531 --> 03:19.574
And the sex.

03:19.657 --> 03:22.035
-Don't forget the sex.
-Oh, I bet she tries to.

03:22.869 --> 03:24.245
-Six.
-Beer?

03:24.329 --> 03:25.622
-Yeah.
-Gomez, get him a beer.

03:25.705 --> 03:28.666
-Hmm, beers are in the fridge.
-Yeah, beers are in the fridge.

03:28.750 --> 03:32.462
So get him a beer
from the fridge, Gomez.

03:34.297 --> 03:36.591
-Wow, so this is...
-(CHUCKLES) Yeah, uh,

03:36.674 --> 03:39.886
-this is a work in progress.
-Okey dokey.

03:39.969 --> 03:42.138
Is it bad for chicken
to be this pink?

03:42.221 --> 03:44.766
Uh, depends. Are we
gonna eat it or revive it?

03:44.849 --> 03:47.602
It's chicken
and shiitake risotto.

03:47.685 --> 03:50.063
With winter squash
and pine nut dressing.

03:51.022 --> 03:52.649
Do any of you know
how to actually cook?

03:52.732 --> 03:53.816
-GOMEZ: Mm-mm.
-CHARISSE: No.

03:53.900 --> 03:55.443
Great. Thanks.

03:55.526 --> 03:56.945
I think I could make
something out of this.

03:57.028 --> 04:00.657
Library Boy taking charge.
I'm experiencing chills.

04:00.740 --> 04:02.533
HENRY, 28: Yeah, good for you.
Give me an apron.

04:02.617 --> 04:04.911
-(DOORBELL BUZZES)
-Is someone else coming?

04:04.994 --> 04:06.037
No.

04:09.499 --> 04:10.792
GOMEZ: Hey, Clare, wait up.

04:10.875 --> 04:13.086
So, Clare never said
you could cook.

04:13.169 --> 04:14.754
Or actually that you exist.

04:15.755 --> 04:17.298
-(CHUCKLES)
-(DOORBELL BUZZES)

04:17.382 --> 04:19.509
-Clare, can I just, uh...
-CLARE ABSHIRE, 20: What?

04:19.592 --> 04:23.930
That guy. (PANTS) I--
I think I've seen him before.

04:24.847 --> 04:26.432
Well, now you're
seeing him again.

04:26.516 --> 04:27.642
(DOORBELL BUZZES)

04:27.725 --> 04:29.686
Okay? So go get my boyfriend
an apron.

04:31.562 --> 04:33.439
(DOORBELL CONTINUES BUZZING)

04:33.523 --> 04:35.900
Foreknowledge can be
helpful sometimes.

04:35.984 --> 04:38.486
Knowing a bit of what's coming
can be strange,

04:38.569 --> 04:41.823
it can be useful,
and sometimes it can be tragedy.

04:41.906 --> 04:45.159
-Sometimes it can be farce.
-And sometimes it can be both.

04:45.243 --> 04:46.703
♪ (GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

04:46.786 --> 04:48.663
So, how long
you've been seeing Clare?

04:48.746 --> 04:50.957
Hmm, complicated question.

04:51.040 --> 04:53.584
No, it isn't.
What's complicated about it?

04:53.668 --> 04:55.753
-Well...
-Well, I live with her.

04:55.837 --> 04:58.006
I see her every day.
When do you see her?

04:59.549 --> 05:02.051
-From time to time.
-(LAUGHS) Sorry?

05:02.135 --> 05:04.554
That was actually really funny.
You just need a bit of context.

05:04.637 --> 05:06.764
Oh, you're still making jokes,
Library Boy?

05:06.848 --> 05:08.558
Actually, I was just
running out of material.

05:08.641 --> 05:09.976
Thank God you're back.

05:10.059 --> 05:12.228
Henry, could you come out here
for a minute?

05:12.311 --> 05:15.481
-Yeah, I totally could.
-Uh, guys, if you could, um,

05:15.565 --> 05:17.734
just give us a moment,
please. Thanks.

05:20.361 --> 05:22.405
It's the door. It's for you.

05:23.156 --> 05:24.866
-Who is it?
-It's you.

05:24.949 --> 05:27.285
-Okay, but who is it?
-(CHUCKLES) You.

05:27.368 --> 05:28.494
-What? Me?
-Yeah.

05:28.578 --> 05:30.079
HENRY, 41: (OVER INTERCOM)
Hey, junior!

05:30.163 --> 05:31.372
I think I just
freaked out Clare.

05:31.456 --> 05:33.041
Yeah, I can actually
still hear you.

05:33.124 --> 05:34.292
Sorry, old man. I'm actually

05:34.375 --> 05:36.085
in the middle
of a very not good moment

05:36.169 --> 05:37.587
which is
still currently transpiring.

05:37.670 --> 05:39.338
Yeah, well, in 13 years,
you're gonna be naked

05:39.422 --> 05:41.090
and running from the police.
You need to let me in.

05:41.174 --> 05:43.092
I just met her friends,
and they hate me already.

05:43.176 --> 05:45.511
This is really not a good moment
for there to be two of me.

05:45.595 --> 05:47.972
Yeah, well...
guess who's coming to dinner.

05:48.056 --> 05:49.390
(SIGHS)

05:49.474 --> 05:52.685
-(SIREN BLARING)
-(DOOR BUZZES, CLICKS OPEN)

05:53.936 --> 05:57.440
♪ ("TIME TRAVELER'S WIFE"
THEME MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

07:04.298 --> 07:05.341
Hello, Henry.

07:14.684 --> 07:16.227
♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

07:19.063 --> 07:21.315
-Uh...
-(BIRDS CHIRPING)

07:21.399 --> 07:22.859
...you switched out my clothes.

07:24.193 --> 07:26.195
Why am I dressed like this?

07:26.279 --> 07:28.364
We're gonna talk
about how you're dressed?

07:30.491 --> 07:31.742
Oh, you look lovely.

07:33.494 --> 07:35.079
It's May 24th.

07:35.163 --> 07:39.584
-HENRY, 41: Oh. Happy birthday!
-2006.

07:41.127 --> 07:43.963
Is that why we're dressed up
like this, for your birthday?

07:44.046 --> 07:48.134
-2006.
-Is that important, 2006?

07:48.217 --> 07:49.302
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

07:49.385 --> 07:51.304
I give up.
Why is that important?

07:54.807 --> 07:55.808
Oh, wait.

07:57.393 --> 07:59.896
-You're 18?
-(CHUCKLES) Today.

08:00.938 --> 08:01.981
Eighteen.

08:02.982 --> 08:05.026
-Okay.
-CLARE, 18: How old are you?

08:05.109 --> 08:07.236
-I'm 41.
-CLARE, 18: Forty-one!

08:07.320 --> 08:10.072
Oh, I like it when you're gray.
It's kinda sweet.

08:10.156 --> 08:12.575
-(CHUCKLES)
-I feel safe when you're gray.

08:13.576 --> 08:16.537
-Come sit with me.
-Why?

08:16.621 --> 08:20.208
Well, because that's what we do.
We sit and we talk.

08:20.708 --> 08:22.084
Yeah, but, uh...

08:22.168 --> 08:23.377
-Yeah, but what?
-You're...

08:24.712 --> 08:25.755
Now you're 18.

08:25.838 --> 08:27.506
-And?
-And I'm married.

08:27.590 --> 08:28.925
-To me.
-Well, no.

08:29.008 --> 08:30.760
-Well, yeah.
-Not right now.

08:30.843 --> 08:32.220
(CHUCKLES) Well, yes, right now.

08:32.303 --> 08:33.471
You're 41, you're married,

08:33.554 --> 08:36.515
and right now,
I'm who you're married to.

08:37.683 --> 08:40.269
How do you think the woman
I left alone in bed,

08:40.353 --> 08:43.439
my wife, is gonna feel about me
slipping back in time

08:43.522 --> 08:46.734
and, you know, basically...
sitting on a blanket

08:46.817 --> 08:48.986
with the 18-year-old version
of herself?

08:49.070 --> 08:49.987
Nostalgic?

08:50.071 --> 08:51.572
-I think she'd be hurt.
-I don't.

08:51.656 --> 08:53.616
-I do.
-This is me we're talking about.

08:53.699 --> 08:55.576
Are you correcting me
on what I'm gonna think?

08:55.660 --> 08:57.203
Wow, we are definitely married.

08:57.286 --> 08:59.121
HENRY, 41: Look, Clare,
there are rules to this.

08:59.205 --> 09:01.207
I-- I made rules for myself
when this all started,

09:01.290 --> 09:02.541
and I'm not breaking them.

09:02.625 --> 09:05.044
You made rules about sitting
on a blanket with a person?

09:05.127 --> 09:06.796
-Well, no.
-A person with whom

09:06.879 --> 09:09.799
you have been regularly sitting
on this very spot?

09:09.882 --> 09:11.008
Yeah, but...

09:12.551 --> 09:13.511
you're 18 now.

09:13.594 --> 09:15.471
-Yes.
-You're all...

09:15.554 --> 09:16.681
CLARE, 18: All what?

09:18.391 --> 09:19.892
I have rules.

09:19.976 --> 09:21.978
(GROANS) You don't need
rules anymore!

09:22.061 --> 09:23.771
-We're done here.
-What do you mean we're done?

09:23.854 --> 09:26.315
-It's May 24th, 2006.
-Your birthday, great.

09:26.399 --> 09:27.650
-Yeah, and?
-And what?

09:27.733 --> 09:28.776
Jesus, don't you remember?

09:28.859 --> 09:32.780
There's 152 meetings
over 12 years.

09:32.863 --> 09:35.032
We are done.

09:35.116 --> 09:37.159
We're saying goodbye.
This is the last time

09:37.243 --> 09:40.621
in this clearing and...
I don't even know for how long.

09:48.921 --> 09:49.964
You okay?

09:55.094 --> 09:57.013
At least tell me for how long.

10:03.060 --> 10:04.186
Two years.

10:04.270 --> 10:05.604
-Two years?
-HENRY, 41: About, yeah.

10:05.688 --> 10:07.982
Then you meet younger me,
and boy does he get a fright.

10:08.065 --> 10:09.650
What am I supposed to do
for two years?

10:09.734 --> 10:12.153
It's your life. All right?
Get on with it.

10:12.236 --> 10:14.822
Don't think about what's coming,
because it'll come anyway.

10:15.573 --> 10:16.824
Do whatever you like.

10:17.575 --> 10:19.493
Meet people. Be with people.

10:19.577 --> 10:21.287
-Be with them?
-Yeah.

10:21.370 --> 10:22.663
-Be with?
-Just, you know.

10:22.747 --> 10:24.915
What, is "be with"
Dad speak for--

10:24.999 --> 10:27.043
Look, Clare,
I'm out there somewhere,

10:27.126 --> 10:28.252
26-year-old me,

10:28.336 --> 10:29.879
and I'm not saving myself
for you,

10:29.962 --> 10:31.547
because I don't even know
you exist.

10:31.630 --> 10:33.799
So please don't save yourself
for me.

10:34.800 --> 10:36.677
Save myself.

10:36.761 --> 10:39.055
-(JASON EVERLEIGH GRUNTING)
-(CLARE, 16, SCREAMS)

10:39.138 --> 10:43.976
♪ (TENSE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

10:44.060 --> 10:46.145
I wanted you to be my first.

10:49.774 --> 10:51.317
Well, I don't want to be yours.

10:57.239 --> 10:58.949
I want to be your last, Clare.

11:05.247 --> 11:07.249
-Two years?
-Yeah.

11:08.542 --> 11:11.545
And a... little while.

11:11.629 --> 11:13.130
Well, how long
is a little while?

11:13.214 --> 11:15.132
Just let it happen.

11:18.469 --> 11:20.471
You've never kissed me,
you know.

11:20.554 --> 11:22.681
Oh, I've kissed you
a million times.

11:23.849 --> 11:26.769
Well, then I expect
you're incredibly good at it.

11:39.740 --> 11:42.785
Hey. Hey! Gotta get up.

11:42.868 --> 11:44.537
-Hmm?
-Gotta get up.

11:44.620 --> 11:47.415
-What?
-Now, please, come on.

11:47.498 --> 11:50.251
-What time is it?
-CLARE, 19: About three.

11:50.334 --> 11:52.420
You gotta go. Come on,
Charisse is coming back.

11:52.503 --> 11:54.255
-(SIGHS)
-(DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE)

11:55.339 --> 11:57.967
(CLARE, 19, SOBS)

12:03.848 --> 12:05.558
(EXHALES)

12:05.641 --> 12:08.602
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

12:10.062 --> 12:13.190
(CLARE, 19, EXHALES, SNIFFLES)

12:13.858 --> 12:14.942
Are you okay?

12:16.277 --> 12:19.029
(VOICE BREAKING) Yeah.
Yeah, fine.

12:20.531 --> 12:22.616
I nearly couldn't find you.

12:22.700 --> 12:27.079
This place, it's so huge.
I never get used to it.

12:28.372 --> 12:31.375
Hey, how do you two afford
this place, anyway?

12:31.459 --> 12:34.628
Do you rob banks?
Can I rob banks too?

12:34.712 --> 12:36.380
It's getting demolished
in three months.

12:37.423 --> 12:39.008
-Oh.
-Except the plans
are gonna change

12:39.091 --> 12:40.676
and it will still be here
in 20 years.

12:40.759 --> 12:41.635
How do you know?

12:41.719 --> 12:43.220
I got a tip off
when I was a kid.

12:43.304 --> 12:45.681
You got a property tip
when you were a kid? (CHUCKLES)

12:45.764 --> 12:46.932
-Who from?
-Jesus, Gomez!

12:47.016 --> 12:50.519
-Can you stop talking?
-Hey. Hey, are you all right?

12:50.603 --> 12:53.314
No! Yeah. (SNIFFLES) I'm fine.

12:53.397 --> 12:57.985
I'm, uh... (PANTS) I'm fine.

12:58.068 --> 13:01.906
Oh, God! It was awful,
wasn't it? Me, I mean.

13:01.989 --> 13:03.782
CLARE, 19: No, of course not.
Why would you think that?

13:03.866 --> 13:05.534
Well, we just had sex
and now you're crying.

13:05.618 --> 13:08.329
It's pretty hard to process that
as a positive response.

13:08.412 --> 13:10.414
I'm not crying
because you're terrible at sex.

13:10.498 --> 13:14.418
I'm crying because of what
we both just did to Charisse.

13:14.502 --> 13:16.545
I'm crying because I just
betrayed my best friend

13:16.629 --> 13:18.172
with my other best friend,
and I've quite possibly

13:18.255 --> 13:21.884
-fucked up the rest of my life.
-Oh, thank God. (CHUCKLES)

13:21.967 --> 13:24.470
Uh, just thank God about
the sex thing.

13:24.553 --> 13:25.971
Not thank God
about the other part.

13:26.055 --> 13:27.181
Obviously, that's...

13:27.264 --> 13:30.100
-That's very bad.
-To be clear, I was drunk.

13:30.809 --> 13:32.520
I hate myself,

13:32.603 --> 13:34.939
and this will never ever
happen again.

13:39.652 --> 13:42.488
(SCOFFS, SIGHS)

13:47.034 --> 13:49.328
You know,
I thought you were a lesbian.

13:49.411 --> 13:51.330
In the circumstances,
that's gonna be hard

13:51.413 --> 13:54.124
-to take as a compliment.
-No, I only thought lesbian,

13:54.208 --> 13:55.417
because you're always alone.

13:55.501 --> 13:57.670
You realize lesbians
aren't alone.

13:57.753 --> 13:59.797
There is a thing
they haven't been telling you.

13:59.880 --> 14:01.048
Who's Henry?

14:04.552 --> 14:05.886
I don't know. Who is he?

14:05.970 --> 14:07.721
You kept saying his name
in your sleep.

14:08.764 --> 14:11.016
Oh. That Henry.

14:11.100 --> 14:12.560
GOMEZ: Yeah, that Henry.

14:13.727 --> 14:16.438
-Who is he?
-My lover.

14:20.067 --> 14:22.361
What? What is it? What?

14:23.445 --> 14:25.447
I thought you
didn't have anyone.

14:25.531 --> 14:27.074
I really thought
that you were alone.

14:27.157 --> 14:28.742
Oh, well,
it was very kind of you

14:28.826 --> 14:29.827
to take pity on me then,

14:29.910 --> 14:31.704
the moment your girlfriend
was in Boston.

14:32.746 --> 14:35.040
Check your back for scratches,
I'm a scratcher.

14:35.124 --> 14:36.584
-I love Charisse.
-Good!

14:36.667 --> 14:38.460
Good, I thought you did,
because you and Charisse

14:38.544 --> 14:40.921
that's the real thing,
so what you need to do now is--

14:41.005 --> 14:42.214
But I love you more!

14:46.051 --> 14:47.761
Okay, there, I said it.

14:52.182 --> 14:53.892
God, it sounds weird
saying it out loud.

14:53.976 --> 14:55.519
I could be patronizing
and tell you

14:55.603 --> 14:57.062
-how you'll get over it.
-Oh, please don't.

14:57.146 --> 14:59.064
CLARE, 19: Instead,
I'm gonna tell you the truth,

14:59.148 --> 15:00.733
